      <text>
        The forest opened into a clearing, and Kira stopped short.

        The facility wasn't a building — not in any sense she understood buildings.
        It was _alive_.

        ¶

        Massive woody vines — each thicker than her torso — wove together in impossible patterns. They formed walls, chambers, archways. The whole structure rose maybe three stories high, sprawling across the clearing like some enormous basket someone had grown instead of built. Bioluminescent patches glowed soft blue-green along the vines, providing light as the purple twilight deepened. And the entire thing moved — just slightly — breathing, growing.

        Holloway — a fluting voice emerging from multiple fruiting bodies sprouting around the entrance — said, "Welcome to Central Coordination! We're so pleased you're here!"

        Scout bounced ahead enthusiastically, tumbling toward one of the vine-gap doorways.

        Kira stared, her brain trying to process living architecture and failing.

        Kira asked, "You built this?"

        Holloway said, "Grew it! Over many seasons. The structural vines responded beautifully to coordination — please, come inside!"

        It was beautiful — weird and organic and completely alien, but beautiful. She was also too exhausted to properly appreciate it.

        Her leg throbbed with each heartbeat. The temporary treatment Remedy had applied was holding, but pain leaked through anyway. She'd been limping through purple forest for — how long? An hour? Two?

        Kira said, "Lead the way."

        Inside, a chamber of smoothly curved woven-vine walls glowed with bioluminescence. A flat vine surface — shaped as a desk — occupied the center. Multiple fruiting bodies dotted the space, all oriented toward her.

        Holloway said, "Let's begin your intake processing!"

        Of course — paperwork.

        Forms appeared — not paper exactly, but thin bark sheets with symbols pressed or carved into the surface. Kira lowered herself carefully onto what might generously be called a seat; her leg thanked her.

        Buddy asked, fascinated, "How are they producing written documentation?"

        Holloway said proudly, "We learned to form symbols — very useful for record-keeping. Now then, let's start with the Visitor Information Sheet. Full legal name?"

        Kira said, "Kira Voss."

        Holloway said, "Home address?"

        Kira stared at the bark form and said, "My ship — which exploded."

        Holloway said, "I see — I'll note: previous residence destroyed, current residence to be determined — and what should I put for your current address?"

        Kira said, "I... don't have one."

        Holloway said, "We'll assign you temporary quarters — after orientation, of course."

        Of course — after.

        Scout bounced sympathetically and rolled closer, the small plant pressing against her uninjured leg — gentle, encouraging. She reached down to touch the fuzzy surface; warm, alive, somehow comforting.

        Holloway said, "Contact information?"

        Kira almost laughed and said, "My communicator died with the ship."

        Holloway said, "Noted — communication devices unavailable due to incident."
      </text>
