      <text>
        The casual way Holloway phrased it — total life upheaval reduced to bureaucratic notation. But there was genuine warmth in that voice, a real desire to help — just filtered through the most absurd framework imaginable.

        Holloway — "Next section: Emergency Contact Information."

        At that, Kira went still.

        Holloway — "Name, relationship, and contact method for your emergency contact."

        Her crew were dead — Captain Torres, Marcus, Lian — all gone. The ship had been her whole world for two years, and that world had exploded. Her family back on Terra Station might as well be in another universe — no ansible, no faster-than-light communication, no way to reach anyone.

        Kira — "I… don't have one."

        Holloway — "No emergency contact? No family or friends?"

        Kira — "My colleagues died in the crash." Her voice stayed level — good. "My family is… unreachable. Light years away. No communication."

        Buddy — "I could serve as emergency contact!"

        Kira — "You're an AI, Buddy. You don't count."

        Buddy — "That seems unnecessarily discriminatory."

        Despite everything — the exhaustion, the pain, the crushing weight of being stranded and alone — she almost laughed.

        Holloway — "We can list the collective as emergency contact — in case of any incident, we'll coordinate appropriate response."

        It was meant to be helpful.

        It made her want to cry.

        ¶

        She was alone here — truly, completely alone, stranded on an alien planet with bureaucratic plants and an over-enthusiastic AI and no one, _no one_, who could help if something went wrong. Who would even know if she died out here?

        Scout pressed harder against her leg — a small, solid weight, present.

        Kira — "Sure. List the collective." Her voice still sounded steady.

        Holloway — "Excellent! And nearest hospital or medical facility?"

        Kira — "You're looking at it."

        Holloway — "Correct! I'll note: on-site medical resources available."

        The wrongness of it settled into her bones. But she kept answering questions. What else was there to do?

        Holloway — "Medical history section — previous injuries or chronic conditions?"

        Kira — "Nothing major."

        Holloway — "Current injuries?"

        Kira gestured at her leg — "Laceration, approximately fifteen centimeters, partial treatment received, requires follow-up care."

        She was learning their language — phrasing things in their framework.

        Holloway — "Any other injuries from the incident?"

        Kira — "Bruises, scrapes, possible concussion. Exhaustion."

        Holloway — "I'll schedule comprehensive medical evaluation post-orientation."

        Kira — "How long is orientation?" she asked carefully.

        Holloway — "Standard protocol is four hours for workplace safety fundamentals!"

        Four _hours_. Four more hours of bureaucracy before proper medical treatment.

        Kira — "My leg—"

        Holloway — "Remedy's temporary treatment should remain effective for six to eight hours according to their documentation — your evaluation is scheduled well within that window!"

        It wasn't wrong. The greenish paste Remedy had applied was holding. The pain was manageable. But four hours of workplace safety training for a crash survivor felt absurd.
      </text>
