        Holloway — "Allergies?"

        Kira listed what she knew. Buddy provided medical data from her file — apparently some of her ship records had survived in his systems.

        Holloway — "Current medications?"

        Kira — "None — because my ship exploded."

        Holloway — "Noted: no current prescriptions."

        The pain in her leg pulsed in time with her heartbeat; sitting helped, but she wanted water and to lie down — she wanted this day to be over. Still, she answered the questions.

        Holloway — "Employment history and skills assessment — current or most recent occupation?"

        Kira — "I'm not applying for a job — I crashed here. I'm stranded."

        Holloway — "Of course — but information about your capabilities helps us understand your needs and how we can best assist!"

        «Sure. Fine. Whatever.»

        Holloway — "Cargo specialist. Certified for grade-three cargo operations, emergency protocols, basic ship maintenance."

        Buddy — "Records: two years on the Meridian, three before that on smaller transports, apprenticeship on Terra Station."

        Holloway — "Excellent background — very thorough documentation — this will be very helpful for your integration."

        Integration. Like she was joining their team instead of being a crashed survivor with nowhere else to go.

        ¶

        The forms continued: education history, technical skills, even hobbies — which seemed like the least relevant question imaginable. Several fruiting bodies consulted with each other, comparing notes and filing information away in that distributed network consciousness.

        Holloway — "All intake documentation complete — you're ready for orientation."

        Kira stood despite her leg protesting sharply; she gritted her teeth. Scout bounced encouragingly toward another chamber — a vine-gap doorway leading deeper into the living structure.

        Holloway — "Orientation covers workplace safety protocols, emergency procedures, and facility guidelines — very important for ensuring a safe and productive environment!"

        Kira — "Great — can't wait."

        Holloway — "We're very excited to have you here, Kira! The first human visitor in many seasons — a wonderful opportunity for cross-species cooperation and learning!"

        They *were* excited. Happy to have her. Trying so incredibly hard to help in the only way they knew how.

        It was just that the way they knew how involved four hours of workplace safety training before treating a leg injury.

        She followed Scout toward the next chamber; the small plant bounced along, occasionally glancing back to make sure she was keeping up.

        Four _hours_ to go.

        Then medical evaluation — then, maybe, she could rest.

        She could — she had to do this. One absurd bureaucratic requirement at a time.
      </text>
